EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold high pressure system settled into the Mid Hudson Valley during the overnight hours of April 26-27. Under a mostly clear sky, and light wind, temperatures fell to or below 32 degrees across portions of Ulster and Dutchess Counties where the growing season had already started. No damage has been reported to the National Weather Service with this freeze.

Canadian high pressure settled into upstate New York early on the morning of October 9. With a mostly clear sky and little or no wind, temperatures dipped to between 28 and 32 degrees across much of Northern Herkimer, Hamilton and Warren counties, thus ending the growing season in these places. No crop damage was reported to the National Weather Service, from this freeze.

A large area of Canadian high pressure built eastward from the Great Lakes to New York and adjacent western New England on the morning of October 16. With a clear sky and no wind, strong radiational cooling took place, which allowed temperatures to dip to, or in many cases, well below freezing across all of eastern New York for the first time since last May, thus ending the growing season. No damage was reported to the National Weather Service as a result of this freeze.

A large Canadian high pressure system became established over eastern New York and adjacent western New England early on May 17. With a clear sky, little or no wind and low humidity, radiational cooling allowed temperatures to dip to, or even a little below the freezing mark in southeastern Warren County, northern Saratoga County,  and southern Washington County, bringing a widespread freeze to both these counties. No problems were reported to the National Weather Service as a result of this freeze.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Canadian high pressure built over northern New York on the morning of June 2. With a mainly clear sky and light wind, ideal radiational cooling took place. By sunrise, temperatures bottomed out around the freezing mark over portions of Hamilton County. No problems were reported to the National Weather Service as a result of this freeze.

A large Canadian high pressure settled in across eastern New York, early on October 23. The sky cleared enough to allow temperatures to fall to the freezing mark or lower across the Mid Hudson Valley, thus ending the growing season in that region.

Before sunrise on May 5, high pressure crested over eastern New York and adjacent western
New England With light wind and clear sky, the air at the earth's surface cooled to below freezing
across most of eastern New York. There were numerous reports of minimum temperatures at or
below 30 degrees. No major agricultural damage was reported to the National Weather Service
from this frost.

Chilly air lingered another day in a portion of eastern New York as a ridge of high pressure
centered over Nova Scotia ridged southwestward across New England into northeastern New
York during the early morning hours of May 6.  Subfreezing air was not as widespread as it
was on May 5, however, a few locations had readings below freezing in southern Warren
County.  Glens Falls had the lowest reported temperature, 29 degrees.  Once again, no serious
agricultural damage was reported to the National Weather Service from this frost.

During the predawn hours on May 13, high pressure over southeastern Quebec Province,
Canada, ridged southeastward into eastern New York and adjacent western New England.
With a clear sky and a light wind, cooling at the earth's surface was optimized.  The
temperatures dropped below freezing for several hours.  New York Dept. of Agriculture and
Markets indicated that there was extensive damage to the fruit crop but could not yet
provide a dollar value to the damage.

Surface high pressure system over western Ontario Province Friday, September 23rd moved east across Quebec Province Saturday morning, September 24th. Overnight low temperatures reached at or below freezing in portions of southern Franklin county, western Essex county and western Clinton county in New York State.

On September 30, a ridge of high pressure over eastern New York State was associated with clear sky and chilly near-calm air.  During the predawn hours, the temperature dipped below freezing in a portion of the southern Adirondack Mountain region.  The minimum temperatures at Big Moose, Stillwater Reservoir, and Old Forge were 29, 31, and 32 degrees respectively.

High pressure over the western Great Lakes with a ridge to Pennsylvania early Thursday, October 20th moved east with the ridge over New England and New York early Friday, October 21st. Clear skies and calm winds resulted in at or below freezing temperatures in most areas overnight. This cold snap ended any growing season after a relatively mild fall season.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: An unusually cold air mass, clear skies and light winds led to a widespread frost, along with subfreezing temperatures during the early morning hours of May 1st. These cold temperatures, combined with the anomalously early blossoming of vegetation due to an early season warm spell, had significant agricultural impact for portions of eastern Schenectady County.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The combination of an unseasonably cold air mass, clear skies and light winds led to widespread freezing temperatures, along with frost across the mid Hudson Valley, Capital District, the Lake George and Saratoga region, and Mohawk Valley of eastern New York during the early morning hours of Thursday May 1st.||The freeze and frost was particularly damaging to fruit trees, as a previous warm spell in mid to late April led to unusually advanced stages of bloom. Preliminary damage estimates were near 20 million dollars in production losses, mainly for apple and peach orchards across the mid Hudson Valley region.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: An unusually cold air mass, clear skies and light winds led to a widespread frost, along with subfreezing temperatures during the early morning hours of May 1st. These cold temperatures, combined with the anomalously early blossoming of vegetation due to an early season warm spell, had significant agricultural impact for portions of northern Washington County.

Temperatures over the Eastern Lake Ontario Region and interior sections of the Western Southern Tier fell below 32 degrees resulting in a widespread freeze over those areas. Specific readings included: 24 in Andover; 25 in Ellicottville; 27 in Franklinville; 28 in Wellsville and Parish; 29 in Warsaw, Attica, Watertown and Harrisburg; 30 in Mexico and Philadelphia and 31 in Turin.

Unseasonably cold Canadian high pressure built across the lower Great Lakes region and settled over New York State. Mainly clear skies, light winds and plenty of cold, dry air associated with this system provided ideal conditions for a hard freeze to occur. Overnight lows ranged from the mid 20s to near the freezing mark closer to the lakeshores.  A sampling of minimum temperatures included:  32 at Fulton; 31 at Port Byron; 29 at Orchard Park, Lyndonville, Rochester, and Alden; 28 at Yorkshire, Sherman and Rose; 27 at Attica, Bristol; 26 at Turin; 25 at Ellicottville, Watertown and 24 at Andover and Pendleton.

An unseasonably cold air mass was ushered into the region on brisk and gusty northwesterly winds in the wake of a strong low pressure system on Saturday, May 8th. Despite cloud cover and continued brisk winds, temperatures dropped into the upper 20s to lower 30s across portions of the eastern Catskills and Mohawk Valley during the early morning hours of Sunday, May 9th. The growing season started early in this area after a stretch of unusually warm temperatures during April. ||In addition, a light coating of snow, up to 1.5 inches, occurred across portions of the western Adirondacks.

A very warm spring resulted in an earlier than normal start to the growing season. Crops were two to three weeks ahead of normal. High pressure brought light winds and clear skies to the region���ideal conditions for radiational cooling. Temperatures fell to below freezing on two consecutive nights. Nighttime temperatures for the 10th and 11th, respectively, included:  Watertown 26 and 25; Lowville 30 and 27; Warsaw 31 and 30; Franklinville 24 and 25; Wales 27 and 27; Jamestown 30 and 27; Avon 30 and 31; Honeoye 32 and 29; and Wellsville 25 and 31. Grapes in portions of the southern tier and Finger Lakes region and stone fruits in the Lake Ontario shore counties were affected.

An unseasonably cold air mass produced temperatures in the mid 20s to lower 30s across east central New York during the early morning hours of Tuesday, May 11th. The growing season started early across east central New York, except for the southern Adirondacks, after a stretch of unusually warm temperatures during April. ||There was frost and freeze damage to fruit trees, including apple, peach, pear, cherry, strawberry and blueberry trees across much of the area.||The temperature at the Albany International Airport dropped to 29 degrees. This tied the old record set back in 1966. The daily records for Albany date back to 1874.

The growing season started early across east central New York, except for the southern Adirondacks, after a stretch of unusually warm temperatures during April. ||There was frost and freeze damage to fruit trees, including apple, peach, pear, cherry, strawberry and blueberry trees across much of the area.||The temperature at the Albany International Airport dropped to 29 degrees. A very warm spring resulted in an earlier than normal start to the growing season. Crops were two to three weeks ahead of normal. High pressure brought light winds and clear skies to the region���ideal conditions for radiational cooling. Temperatures fell to below freezing on two consecutive nights. Nighttime temperatures for the 10th and 11th, respectively, included:  Watertown 26 and 25; Lowville 30 and 27; Warsaw 31 and 30; Franklinville 24 and 25; Wales 27 and 27; Jamestown 30 and 27; Avon 30 and 31; Honeoye 32 and 29; and Wellsville 25 and 31. Grapes in portions of the southern tier and Finger Lakes region and stone fruits in the Lake Ontario shore counties were affected.
